In order to find the object\u8217\'92s location relative to the cameras in either pair of given dimensions, the camera\u8217\'92s angular range of vision ((-)v1 and (-)v2) in the x/y dimension and the camera\u8217\'92s rotation north of the line c1/c2 ((-)i1 and (-)i2) must be known. Object detection returns the x or y component as a number between 0 and 1 directly proportional to the object\u8217\'92s displacement from the left side of p11/p12 and p22/p21, which are the edges of the camera\u8217\'92s field of vision. The a variable therefore determines how much of the range of vision (-)v should apply to (-)c. With this component as a, the equation for (-)c1 is (-)i + (-)v*(1-a), and the equation for (-)c2 is (-)i + (-)v*a. With (-)c1 and (-)c2 found, we can now find (-)t with 2pi-((-)c1+(-)c2) (fig 2) and find c1/t and c2/t with the law of sines, the recently found angles, and (-)t. This nets the equations c1-t = d*sin((-)c2)/sin((-)t), and c2/t = d*sin((-)c1)/sin((-)t). This nets the magnitude of both the z and x/y displacement from the object for each camera.}
