The object\u8217\'92s distance from the camera is necessary to find possible object orientations with the bounding boxes provided by the object detectors. In order to find the object\u8217\'92s orientation relative to the camera, refer to fig 4. Right triangle c1/m1/t can be solved by finding (-)m1 as (-)c1-(-)v1/2-(-)i1 and (-)m2 as (-)c2-(-)v2/2-(-)i2. The lengths of t/m1 and t/m2 are the negative x/y displacements from the cameras, and the lengths of m1/c1 and m2/c2 are the positive z displacements from the cameras. t/m1 = t/c1*sin((-)m1), m1/c1= t/c1*cos((-)m1), t/m2 = t/c2*sin((-)m2), m2/c2 = t/c2*cos((-)m2). The x/y and z displacements for camera 1 are -t/m1 and m1/c1 respectively, and the x/y and z displacements for camera 2 are -t/m2 and m1/c2 respectively.}
